@startuml
title casbinjs/core - Component View and Responsibility Boundaries

skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam shadowing false

actor ConsumerApp as Consumer
database "External Endpoint / Data Source" as Endpoint

package "casbinjs/core" {
  interface "Authorizer" as AuthorizerContract
  component "Authorizer Facade" as AuthorizerFacade
  component "Input Normalizer" as InputNormalizer
  component "Enforcer Factory" as EnforcerFactory
  component "Facade State" as FacadeState
}

package "casbin-core" {
  component "Enforcer" as Enforcer
  component "Model Evaluation" as Evaluation
  component "Policy Processing" as PolicyProcessing
}

Endpoint --> Consumer : AuthorizationPayload

Consumer --> AuthorizerContract : can / canAny / canAll
Consumer --> AuthorizerContract : replacePayload\nsetPermissions\naddPermission\nremovePermission
AuthorizerContract <|.. AuthorizerFacade

Consumer --> InputNormalizer : provide payload / options
InputNormalizer --> AuthorizerFacade : normalized input

AuthorizerFacade --> FacadeState : keep facade-level state
AuthorizerFacade --> EnforcerFactory : create / configure enforcer
EnforcerFactory --> Enforcer : initialize with model / policies
AuthorizerFacade --> Enforcer : delegate checks
Enforcer --> Evaluation : apply matcher logic
Enforcer --> PolicyProcessing : process policies / roles

note right of Endpoint
Outside library boundary.
Consumer owns transport:
tRPC, REST, GraphQL,
SSR props, static JSON, etc.
end note

note bottom of AuthorizerFacade
casbinjs/core owns:
- vanilla-ready Authorizer interface
- input normalization
- ergonomic initialization contracts
- convenience methods
- delegation to casbin-core
end note

note bottom of FacadeState
Facade-level state only.
Not a separate authorization engine.
end note

note bottom of Enforcer
casbin-core owns:
- enforcer implementation
- matcher evaluation
- policy processing
- model-driven authorization semantics
end note
@enduml
